<h2>Event in November 2019</h2>
<br><br>
In November 2019 the northern central Mediterranean region was hit several times by abundant precipitation events. Largest number of days (10 days and more) with precipitation sums greater than 10 mm (R10mm) were recorded along the western coasts of Italy, southern France, the Balkans and the Iberian Peninsula as well as along the southern slope of the Alps (Figure 1). The rainfall amounts accumulated over the whole month are also very impressive in these regions, reaching values of 250mm and more in large parts of Italy for example. In Italy, monthly precipitation values were in some areas double (for example in the Po basin) or even triple or quadruple (for example in south Tyrol) the normal amounts (that is the average over the reference period). For Italy, November 2019 finished as the rainiest November ever.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/nov2019/Stateofclimate_IndicesTest_r10mm_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_r10mmETCCDI_baselayers_overlay_2019-11-15T12-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/nov2019/Stateofclimate_IndicesTest_r10mm_2019_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_r10mmETCCDI_baselayers_overlay_2019-11-15T12-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/nov2019/Stateofclimate_IndicesTest_r10mm_2019_month_nc__2019-11-15T12-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/nov2019/Stateofclimate_IndicesTest_r10mm_2019_month_nc__2019-11-15T12-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/nov2019/Stateofclimate_IndicesTest_r10mm_anom_2019_1981-2010_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_r10mmETCCDI_baselayers_overlay_2019-11-15T12-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/nov2019/Stateofclimate_IndicesTest_r10mm_anom_2019_1981-2010_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_r10mmETCCDI_baselayers_overlay_2019-11-15T12-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/nov2019/Stateofclimate_IndicesTest_r10mm_anom_2019_1981-2010_month_nc__2019-11-15T12-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/nov2019/Stateofclimate_IndicesTest_r10mm_anom_2019_1981-2010_month_nc__2019-11-15T12-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: R10mm - Heavy precipitation days in November 2019 (left) and anomaly w.r.t. 1981-2010 (right)</em>
<br><br>
These abundant precipitation amounts were due to several Mediterranean storms occurring between 12 and 24 November. First, Medicane TRUDY developed on 12 November from the low pressure area DETLEF (see Figure 2 left). The term medicane is a word blend of Mediterranean and hurricane and refers to intense and destructive mesoscale cyclones exhibiting several similarities with tropical hurricanes. TRUDY brought heavy rain especially to Italy and the Balkans coasts. In Italy up to 90 mm of rain fell on 12 November, on the Balkans coasts up to 78 mm. In the southern Alps TRUDY brought fresh snow quantities of more than 1m as well as strong winds.
As soon as Medicane TRUDY had left, low HEINER (see Figure 1, middle) started heading towards Italy and the Alps. This time, largest amounts of precipitation occurred mainly in the south and east of Austria. Almost 140mm accumulated in 24 hours. At lower altitudes, these fell as rain, at higher altitudes as snow, resulting in floods and enormous amounts of fresh snow. Furthermore, the strong air pressure gradient in Austria caused widespread strong winds and gale force gusts.
In the night from 22 to 23 November, LUIS II (Figure 1, right) moved across the Bay of Biscay and reached the coast of southwestern France on 23 November. Especially along the Atlantic coast of the Iberian Peninsula, stormy winds and abundant precipitation occurred. Several stations in France and Spain recorded more than 100 mm in 24h. But also parts of Italy experienced again heavy precipitation exceeding 100 mm in 24h at several places (on 24 November).
<br><br>
<a href="../images/nov2019/SoC_2019November_event_Figure2.png"><img alt="" src="../images/nov2019/SoC_2019November_event_Figure2.png" width="500px"></a>
<br><br>
Figure 2: Weather analysis map of 11 November 00UTC (left), 15 November 00UTC (middle) and 24 November 00UTC (right) (source: DWD)
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for November 2019</h2>
<br><br>
In eastern Europe both the number of warm day-times (figure 3) and the number of warm nights (figure 4) was much larger than normal, and the number of frost days (figure 5) was much less than normal. Also in the Iberian Peninsula the number of warm nights was larger than normal, but, surprisingly, the number of cold day-times (figure 6) was larger than normal as well. In Scandinavia both the number of cold day-times and the number of cold nights (figure 7) was larger than normal.
